1
00:01:08,200 --> 00:01:11,300
Stop! Stop!

2
00:01:16,100 --> 00:01:18,500
You murderer!

3
00:01:30,600 --> 00:01:32,700
Socrates Fortlow.

4
00:01:34,500 --> 00:01:38,900
His mother named him Socrates
because it was a wise man's name.

5
00:01:39,300 --> 00:01:44,800
She couldn't learn him how to write,
but his name was from someone smart.

6
00:01:52,700 --> 00:01:58,300
He was a violent man.
He would come up hard.

7
00:01:58,700 --> 00:02:01,400
The rage he carried
brought him to prison.

8
00:02:01,700 --> 00:02:05,600
But the correctional authority
was not able to stem his anger.

9
00:02:09,700 --> 00:02:12,500
Socrates was a solitary man.

10
00:02:12,800 --> 00:02:16,300
He kept his own company with
nothing but hurt in his pockets...

11
00:02:16,600 --> 00:02:20,200
and half forgotten memories
for family and friends.

12
00:03:29,700 --> 00:03:32,100
Bottles and cans.

13
00:03:33,100 --> 00:03:37,400
Bottles and cans,
and back alleys and gutters.

14
00:03:37,800 --> 00:03:40,600
Dumpsters and front yards.

15
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:46,600
It's all we have left to make a living.
To have a little dignity in our lives.

16
00:03:48,400 --> 00:03:51,200
Socrates roamed the streets...

17
00:03:51,500 --> 00:03:55,300
because at least he could say
he was his own man.

18
00:03:58,700 --> 00:04:03,600
When he left prison,
he ran as though he had escaped.

19
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:09,400
They paid him 733 dollars
for 18 years hard labour.

20
00:04:09,800 --> 00:04:13,300
He put the money in his pocket
and took the bus to Los Angeles.

21
00:04:13,700 --> 00:04:16,200
That was ten months ago.

22
00:04:18,100 --> 00:04:21,700
He had heard LA was a big
rambling bunch of towns...

23
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:25,900
where everybody is in too much of
a hurry to remember your face.

24
00:04:26,300 --> 00:04:29,600
An ex-con would need
that kind of anonymity.

25
00:04:37,800 --> 00:04:42,600
I first met Socrates when I was
walking past a construction site.

26
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:46,100
He was looking for work, but the
foreman said that he was too old.

27
00:04:46,400 --> 00:04:49,500
Working construction
was a young man's game.

28
00:04:49,900 --> 00:04:53,000
It took three men to throw
Socrates out of there.

29
00:04:53,300 --> 00:04:59,900
He had lived so close to the edge for
so long that he was bound to get cut.

30
00:05:02,800 --> 00:05:06,000
Good morning, Socco.
- Yeah, if it doesn't rain.

31
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:09,100
How are you doing?

32
00:05:09,500 --> 00:05:13,800
Just that flu I had last month
got me some aching.

33
00:05:14,200 --> 00:05:19,400
You want to play some dominoes?
- No man, I got to get to West LA.

34
00:05:19,800 --> 00:05:23,200
What are you doing way over there?
- I'm looking for a job.

35
00:05:23,500 --> 00:05:27,200
Where?
- Bounty Supermarket.

36
00:05:27,600 --> 00:05:32,300
Do you think they're going to hire you?
- They must, man. I can't...

37
00:05:32,800 --> 00:05:35,700
scoop up garbage
for the rest of my life.

38
00:05:40,100 --> 00:05:42,200
Hey man, I know karate!

39
00:05:45,100 --> 00:05:47,800
What is going on?

40
00:05:49,200 --> 00:05:52,100
Leave the man alone.
- Step the fuck back.

41
00:05:52,400 --> 00:05:54,500
Unless you want some of this?

42
00:06:02,900 --> 00:06:08,200
I didn't do shit, man.
- See what you did to my hand, boy?

43
00:06:10,900 --> 00:06:14,800
What's going on?
- Nothing, man.

44
00:06:15,100 --> 00:06:21,200
There is no problem going on here.
Socco, you need anything, man?

45
00:06:21,700 --> 00:06:24,800
We don't do business
with troublemakers.

46
00:06:25,100 --> 00:06:29,400
Come on now, Mr Keene.
We haven't got time...

47
00:06:30,600 --> 00:06:35,200
33, 34, 35, 36...

48
00:06:35,600 --> 00:06:40,400
...36.75. All right, Socco.
- Why are you paying me in change?

49
00:06:40,800 --> 00:06:46,400
We got too much change
from the crushing machines.

50
00:06:47,900 --> 00:06:50,600
If you don't want the money,
why don't you just give it back.

51
00:06:51,500 --> 00:06:54,300
And drag your cans
back out in the street.

52
00:07:05,800 --> 00:07:10,900
Why are you mad?
- Marlon made me mad.

53
00:07:11,300 --> 00:07:16,200
Markham pisses me off.
He will not even take up for himself.

54
00:07:16,600 --> 00:07:22,000
Not everybody is that brave.
I don't mind if a man is scared.

55
00:07:22,500 --> 00:07:27,000
They are just plain stupid.
Neither of them heard a word I said.

56
00:07:27,400 --> 00:07:30,600
Heard you say what?
- What I said to the white man.

57
00:07:30,900 --> 00:07:34,600
What did you say?
- Come on, quit it!

58
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:36,600
What's the matter, Socco?

59
00:07:39,700 --> 00:07:44,900
He had applied for work at almost
every supermarket in South Central.

60
00:07:45,300 --> 00:07:47,100
He went farther away...

61
00:07:47,400 --> 00:07:51,700
so they couldn't recognize him
as a bottles and cans man.

62
00:07:52,100 --> 00:07:55,700
If you were finding
and totting cans...

63
00:07:56,000 --> 00:07:58,600
they looked at you
like you were a bum.

64
00:08:26,900 --> 00:08:29,000
Can I help you?

65
00:08:31,200 --> 00:08:35,100
I came for an application.
- For what?

66
00:08:35,400 --> 00:08:37,300
For a job.

67
00:08:39,500 --> 00:08:43,000
How old are you, sir?
- That's against the law.

68
00:08:43,400 --> 00:08:48,000
You cannot discriminate against
colour, sex, religion...

69
00:08:48,400 --> 00:08:51,000
infirmity or age.
That's the law.

70
00:08:51,300 --> 00:08:54,800
I know that.
There is just no job.

71
00:08:55,100 --> 00:08:58,600
Why don't you come back in the fall?

72
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:01,000
Hey, hold on.

73
00:09:05,700 --> 00:09:12,000
I came for an application. You must give
me an application. That's the law, too.

74
00:09:13,600 --> 00:09:15,600
Wait here.

75
00:09:37,700 --> 00:09:39,400
Here.

76
00:09:41,100 --> 00:09:44,600
I need a pencil.
- Just send it in.

77
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:50,200
I didn't come here for a piece of paper.
I came here to apply for a job.

78
00:09:56,000 --> 00:09:57,500
Thank you.

79
00:10:21,700 --> 00:10:24,100
I am Miss Grimes. Can I help you?

80
00:10:24,400 --> 00:10:28,000
I have some questions.
- What is it you don't understand?

81
00:10:28,300 --> 00:10:31,900
Why do you want to know
whether I have a car?

82
00:10:34,100 --> 00:10:36,700
Where is this address?
- In Watts.

83
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:42,300
That's just too far to go by bus.
- Look, I can get here.

84
00:10:42,700 --> 00:10:46,100
I'll send this to the main office.
If it clears, we'll give you a call.

85
00:10:46,600 --> 00:10:50,900
That's a problem.
I don't have a phone.

86
00:10:51,400 --> 00:10:55,400
We need a phone number,
that's how we check your residence.

87
00:10:55,700 --> 00:10:57,700
You can send it to me.

88
00:11:00,300 --> 00:11:05,400
Send it in for me anyway. I'll come
down myself to find out what they said.

89
00:11:05,800 --> 00:11:08,700
You don't understand...
- Send it in for me.

90
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:11,100
It's not going to make any difference.

91
00:11:33,400 --> 00:11:37,400
Shut the door, Mr Fortlow.
There are too many flies.

92
00:11:40,200 --> 00:11:43,100
How is it going, lula?
- All right.

93
00:11:44,600 --> 00:11:47,000
Have you been collecting cans?

94
00:11:50,500 --> 00:11:55,300
I've got my routes down.
I have 17 regular customers.

95
00:11:55,700 --> 00:11:59,700
I almost made 37 dollars today.
- In change?

96
00:12:00,800 --> 00:12:05,700
The clerks in that redemption centre
want to treat a man like a dog.

97
00:12:06,100 --> 00:12:10,700
That's why I want a real job. So,
I don't need to hurt one of those fools.

98
00:12:11,100 --> 00:12:14,800
That's the way white folks treat you.
- It's not always the white folks...

99
00:12:15,200 --> 00:12:20,900
Today I tried to show a black man
how he has to respect another.

100
00:12:21,300 --> 00:12:25,000
Did you have this checked?
Well, you should.

101
00:12:25,400 --> 00:12:29,800
This could get infected.
- I have had plenty shots in my days.

102
00:12:30,200 --> 00:12:33,900
I might get a broken jaw,
but definitely no lockjaw.

103
00:12:35,600 --> 00:12:39,000
Where did you look for work?
- In a supermarket.

104
00:12:39,300 --> 00:12:43,500
I am capable of putting
groceries in a bag.

105
00:12:43,900 --> 00:12:49,200
A box boy? Mr Fortlow,
you are way too good for that.

106
00:12:49,700 --> 00:12:53,000
But I can pay the rent.

107
00:12:54,300 --> 00:12:56,500
You could work for me.

108
00:12:57,700 --> 00:13:01,100
You could work here for me.

109
00:13:02,600 --> 00:13:04,500
You motherfucker, you killed him.

110
00:13:07,900 --> 00:13:11,900
No, I couldn't work
in such a small space.

111
00:13:12,300 --> 00:13:14,800
I would go crazy like that.

112
00:13:17,800 --> 00:13:20,700
What do you want to eat?
- That big meat loaf plate.

113
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:23,900
I could use it.
I walked a lot today.

114
00:13:32,300 --> 00:13:35,600
What's that?
- The meat loaf plate.

115
00:13:35,900 --> 00:13:41,000
That is half of what you normally serve.
- That's exactly what I serve my clients.

116
00:13:41,500 --> 00:13:44,100
The big plate is for a special person.

117
00:13:50,400 --> 00:13:54,800
Every night Socrates
gave himself a grade.

118
00:13:55,200 --> 00:13:59,400
He once made a promise.
A dark oath.

119
00:13:59,800 --> 00:14:04,000
He swore he would never hurt
another person except to do good.

120
00:14:04,400 --> 00:14:10,800
He wrote down his failures,
when no good had been accomplished.

121
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:26,200
Teresa was the woman
who loved him before he went bad.

122
00:14:26,600 --> 00:14:30,400
But even a long-suffering woman
will let you go...

123
00:14:30,800 --> 00:14:33,600
after murder and rape.

124
00:14:33,900 --> 00:14:37,600
She never wrote him in prison.
But he kept her picture...

125
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:41,700
and told her good night
before he went to bed.

126
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:07,400
What are you doing there, boy?

127
00:15:08,300 --> 00:15:09,900
I asked you a question.

128
00:15:11,100 --> 00:15:14,500
Where do you think you are going?
What's in the box?

129
00:15:14,900 --> 00:15:17,700
What is in it? Put it down.

130
00:15:19,500 --> 00:15:21,500
Come here.

131
00:15:22,900 --> 00:15:25,600
Let me go, man. Let me go!

132
00:15:28,900 --> 00:15:30,800
Pick it up.

133
00:15:32,400 --> 00:15:34,200
Hurry up.

134
00:15:35,600 --> 00:15:40,600
Pick it up, you heard what I said.
Come on, pick it up.

135
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:42,600
Let's go.

136
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:45,100
Sit down.

137
00:15:47,900 --> 00:15:51,500
Why did you kill Dexter, asshole?

138
00:15:52,100 --> 00:15:56,400
You heard me.
- I have never killed somebody, mister.

139
00:15:56,900 --> 00:15:59,500
Sit your little narrow ass down.

140
00:16:08,300 --> 00:16:10,500
This is my friend, Dexter.

141
00:16:10,900 --> 00:16:15,500
You are crazy, that's a chicken, man.
A bird cannot be a friend.

142
00:16:17,900 --> 00:16:21,400
You have to pluck it.
Because you killed it.

143
00:16:21,800 --> 00:16:24,200
I am not playing with you, boy.

144
00:16:39,500 --> 00:16:42,400
What is this?
- I plucked it.

145
00:16:42,700 --> 00:16:46,400
If you don't know how to pluck
a chicken, then why did you kill it?

146
00:16:46,800 --> 00:16:48,500
I don't know.

147
00:16:48,900 --> 00:16:52,900
Maybe there is some old lady
who wants to buy it.

148
00:16:53,300 --> 00:16:56,100
Why did you kill this chicken?

149
00:16:57,200 --> 00:17:02,400
Because I hated it. It was always
crowing like a sick old man.

150
00:17:04,100 --> 00:17:08,400
Do you live around here?
- I live over on Hooper.

151
00:17:09,900 --> 00:17:13,000
You can't hear
a rooster from over there.

152
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:19,100
Get back over there and pluck
all the feathers out.

153
00:17:20,700 --> 00:17:24,600
And when you are finished, cut him
open with that knife over there.

154
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:27,200
And make sure you rinse out
all the blood.

155
00:17:27,700 --> 00:17:29,500
All of it.

156
00:17:38,700 --> 00:17:40,900
What's your name?
- Darryl.

157
00:17:41,200 --> 00:17:44,300
Are you going to do something
with that knife?

158
00:17:51,000 --> 00:17:56,100
We are going to make a dish with
green beans, rice and stewed chicken.

159
00:17:56,500 --> 00:17:59,800
It's going to take a while,
but it will be good.

160
00:18:00,200 --> 00:18:02,600
Clean up those feathers.

161
00:18:08,400 --> 00:18:11,600
Are you hungry?
- Hell, yeah.

162
00:18:12,000 --> 00:18:15,700
That's real good.
A boy should be hungry.

163
00:18:17,200 --> 00:18:22,100
What is that supposed to mean?
- Hunger tells you what you are missing.

164
00:18:22,500 --> 00:18:28,000
Is that some friend to you?
Is hunger your friend, too?

165
00:18:28,400 --> 00:18:33,200
'Hungry, Horny, How come',
they all are my friends.

166
00:18:33,600 --> 00:18:35,700
My best friends.

167
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:40,100
A man must have good friends
to make it through penitentiary.

168
00:18:40,800 --> 00:18:45,700
My daddy is up in the city jail.
At least he was.

169
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:49,000
Died, though.

170
00:19:18,400 --> 00:19:20,200
Can I go now?

171
00:19:21,400 --> 00:19:25,500
You cannot go until you tell.
- What do I tell you?

172
00:19:34,200 --> 00:19:38,200
I am not afraid of you.
- Yes, you are. You are no fool.

173
00:19:40,100 --> 00:19:42,100
Now, come on, Darryl.

174
00:19:45,500 --> 00:19:49,100
Tell it and you can go.
- What do I tell you?

175
00:19:49,400 --> 00:19:51,500
You killed somebody.

176
00:19:52,400 --> 00:19:58,300
I'm not going to turn you in. You did
not know that Dexter was a chicken.

177
00:19:58,800 --> 00:20:02,200
You thought that I knew
something about you.

178
00:20:03,400 --> 00:20:05,700
I am not a judge.

179
00:20:07,200 --> 00:20:09,500
But you will have to talk to me.

180
00:20:11,100 --> 00:20:13,500
Nobody is coming to save you.

181
00:20:23,500 --> 00:20:26,000
It was not my fault.

182
00:20:27,100 --> 00:20:31,000
We were looking at two people
with Phillip in the Baldwin Hills.

183
00:20:45,900 --> 00:20:48,500
Incredible.
- Shut up.

184
00:20:55,200 --> 00:20:57,800
Darryl, grab his pants.

185
00:20:59,300 --> 00:21:01,200
Go.

186
00:21:05,300 --> 00:21:07,900
How are you doing?

187
00:21:09,500 --> 00:21:12,300
Shit.
- Kids, come here.

188
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:16,400
I'm going to kick your butt.

189
00:21:17,800 --> 00:21:19,700
Hey, come back.

190
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:25,400
My cousins left me.
Can I go with you?

191
00:21:25,700 --> 00:21:29,400
Go on, man, get away.
- You'd better get out of here, fool.

192
00:21:29,900 --> 00:21:31,800
Go on.

193
00:21:35,500 --> 00:21:37,200
Get away.

194
00:21:39,100 --> 00:21:42,100
Please.
- Come on, punk.

195
00:21:44,300 --> 00:21:47,300
I've had it with you, piece of shit.
- Come on, man, don't.

196
00:21:50,300 --> 00:21:53,500
Leave that fat ass little nigger alone.

197
00:21:54,000 --> 00:21:56,400
No, man, leave him alone.

198
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:07,000
Is he dead?

199
00:22:12,900 --> 00:22:15,300
Anybody found him yet?

200
00:22:15,600 --> 00:22:18,500
Phillip said he will kill anybody
who talks about it.

201
00:22:24,600 --> 00:22:27,000
I have to go to the bathroom.

202
00:22:37,600 --> 00:22:41,700
Socrates believed every man
had his own load to shoulder.

203
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:44,900
He never cared about another killer...

204
00:22:45,300 --> 00:22:50,500
but when he thought about that skinny
boy, he realized he had been wrong.

205
00:22:56,300 --> 00:22:58,800
You and your friends did wrong,
Darryl.

206
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:05,800
I am just talking to you
as one black man to another.

207
00:23:06,200 --> 00:23:10,800
If you don't know when you have
done wrong, life is not worth a damn.

208
00:23:11,700 --> 00:23:13,700
Can I go now?

209
00:23:15,800 --> 00:23:20,200
Do you live with your mother?
- No, with foster parents.

210
00:23:20,600 --> 00:23:25,800
I don't want to go to jail.
- You are right. That will not solve it.

211
00:23:27,100 --> 00:23:30,300
It's better to shoot yourself
than to go to jail.

212
00:23:35,700 --> 00:23:37,900
Does your foster mom cook for you?

213
00:23:40,100 --> 00:23:43,100
Most of the time she doesn't
even know where I am.

214
00:23:55,300 --> 00:24:00,900
You can always come back here
and we'll cook together.

215
00:24:04,500 --> 00:24:06,600
Why did they put you in jail?

216
00:24:11,600 --> 00:24:15,500
I killed a man and a woman.
- A white man?

217
00:24:22,600 --> 00:24:24,700
Bye.

218
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:27,200
So long, little brother.

219
00:24:31,600 --> 00:24:33,700
I'm sorry about your chicken.

220
00:24:35,700 --> 00:24:38,800
He wasn't mine.
He belongs to Miss Walker.

221
00:24:50,000 --> 00:24:56,900
He wondered about the boy and
the rooster that always awoke him.

222
00:24:57,400 --> 00:25:00,200
The rooster was hoarse
in his old age.

223
00:25:00,600 --> 00:25:03,200
Sometimes his crow was a whisper.

224
00:25:03,500 --> 00:25:06,700
But at least that motherfucker tried.

225
00:25:33,800 --> 00:25:35,500
Corina?

226
00:25:38,300 --> 00:25:42,900
What are you doing here?
I mean, how is it?

227
00:25:43,300 --> 00:25:47,100
Have you seen Howard?
- Is he missing?

228
00:25:47,500 --> 00:25:51,200
We had a fight.
- And he walked out?

229
00:25:51,500 --> 00:25:55,600
He is a damn fool.
- He was just very mad.

230
00:25:56,000 --> 00:25:59,800
Do you know where he is?
- Come on in and drink a coffee.

231
00:26:00,200 --> 00:26:03,600
No. I just need to know
if you've seen him.

232
00:26:04,800 --> 00:26:10,600
No, honey, I haven't seen him. But
I will look for him, if you want me to.

233
00:26:12,600 --> 00:26:15,700
Are you sure
you don't want to come inside?

234
00:26:16,800 --> 00:26:20,400
I have to get back home
to my children.

235
00:26:24,200 --> 00:26:27,600
If you see him, don't tell him
I came over here, okay?

236
00:26:27,900 --> 00:26:31,700
Just call me
if you find out where he is.

237
00:26:45,400 --> 00:26:50,600
Ted is sick. He can't make it today.
Can you come back tomorrow?

238
00:26:51,100 --> 00:26:55,800
Man, what are we supposed to do
with these cans until tomorrow?

239
00:26:56,200 --> 00:26:58,400
